INSERT INTO `en_cms_news` (`id`, `title`, `order`, `display`, `archive`, `txt`, `short_txt`, `_date`, `image`, `folder`) VALUES
(96, 'New updates for our iPhone app', 16, 1, 1, '<div style="text-align:justify;font-family:helvetica,sans-serif">Get even more accurate values for your exact vehicle with our new kilometres adjustment calculator. We’re taking the guessing out of readjusting values for vehicles with higher or lower than average odometer readings with this addition to our app. Visit the App Store and download the update to receive this great new feature.  </div>', '<p><span style="font-size:medium;font-family:helvetica,sans-serif;text-align:justify">Get even more accurate values for your exact vehicle with our new kilometres adjustment calculator. We’re taking the guessing out of readjusting values for vehicles with higher or lower than average odometer readings with this addition to our app. Visit the App Store and download the update to receive this great new feature.</span></p>', '2011-01-31', '1328894002.jpeg', '96'),
(102, 'theCarGuide for Android', 15, 1, 1, '<span style="text-align:left">We will launch our much loved </span><span style="color:#339999;text-align:left">theCarGuide</span><span style="text-align:left">&nbsp;app for Android devices soon.&nbsp;Users will now be able to take our values with them everywhere they go.&nbsp;The Android version will also be available <span style="color:#339999">FREE</span> to all subscribers. Whether its out on a test drive, in the office or simply for settling curiosity, you''ll be hooked on our accurate used values app for Android.</span>', '<p><span style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif;font-size:medium">We will launch our much loved&nbsp;theCarGuide&nbsp;app for Android devices soon.&nbsp;Users will now be able to take our values with them everywhere they go.&nbsp;The Android version will also be available&nbsp;FREE&nbsp;to all subscribers. Whether its out on a test drive, in the office or simply for settling curiosity, you''ll be hooked on our accurate used values app for Android. </span> <br /></span></p>', '2012-02-29', '1331632935.jpeg', '102'),
(105, 'Welcome to MTP.ie', 14, 1, 1, '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/6SN7HXc2N_I" frameborder="0"></iframe>', '<iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/6SN7HXc2N_I" frameborder="0"></iframe>', '2012-03-14', '', '105'),
(108, 'Car servicing -  Not a waste of money', 12, 1, 1, '<p style="text-align:justify">Unless you are a particularly discerning motorist, the likelihood is that you are unable to distinguish the performance of a properly or indeed recently serviced vehicle from one that hasn’t had an oil enema since it left the factory floor. And blaming the recession on a lackadaisical attitude to car servicing is a bit like blaming the lack of time in the evening to do the housework. The truth is, neither task has ever been able to exude the kind of enthusiasm required to proactively tend to matters. It is not until things in these areas extend beyond a reasonable tolerance that most of us decide to intervene. However, cars aren’t inanimate and without appropriate care they will start to make noises that hurt your ears and your wallets.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><br /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify">So why do Irish motorists tend to neglect something which can have such obvious negative repercussions. Firstly, it is my belief that the obscurity of the improvements made from servicing go some way to turning people off looking after their vehicles. How many of you would notice if brake discs have been changed? What about an oil filter? Spark plugs then? Or coolant? A timing belt even? These are all integral parts to some service procedures and yet they do not exhibit any kind of noticeable difference to the performance of an ordinarily properly maintained vehicle. Of course there are fuel efficiency gains to be had but driving attitudes vary on a daily basis so even the most frugal car can return average fuel consumption readings if the owner adopts a particularly heavy foot over the course of a tank of fuel. Nobody enjoys spending money on “invisible” items regardless of how significant and cost effective they are in the long term. Topping a car up with oil every few thousand kilometres simply will not do. Just like carrying defibrillator pads with you everywhere you go might prevent you from dying from heart attack should you endure one, they’re no match for eating healthily and getting oneself checked over every so often.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><br /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify">Of course cost is a substantial barrier to most people servicing their cars. Servicing your vehicle is at best a sensible and mature ownership responsibility not just to oneself as the owner but to the dealer who trades your car in and the prospective owner (which might be you unless you always purchase new vehicles) who may ultimately benefit from your practicality. At its worst, vehicle maintenance is a necessary evil. Either way, an unserviced, poorly maintained car will culminate in somebody footing the bill and this impacts on a number of people. I compiled a survey recently and sent it to motor dealers for their involvement. I was largely unsurprised by the results of my closed questions namely, that 66% of them postulated that less than half of the cars being traded into them had full service histories. This was despite another statistic which claimed that 86% of dealers most frequently trade in vehicles 3 years old and younger. This means that many new car purchasers do not continue to service their cars beyond the first or second service intervals. What was surprising was the additional comments some dealers dutifully provided which comprised a noticeable drop in workshop activity and a dramatic rise in the cost of parts with special emphasis on tyres being among the consumables most affected by price increases. A further 63% of&nbsp; dealers highlighted that the typical reconditioning cost of a vehicle to ensure its salability was in excess of €500 and it could reach close to €1,000 depending on the vehicle or the extent of the parts requiring replacement. These last figures should not be considered as a defense for allowing services to lapse beyond their due dates so that a motor dealer can bear the cost but rather the opposite. They should serve as an explanation to those who trade vehicles in as to the reasons behind varying trade in allowances and ultimately the difference in what a car will make. And in any case, if vehicles were maintained to a standard far in excess than is the present situation, everyone would benefit.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><br /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify">Far be it from me to call anyone I do not know a liar but on an inordinate number of occasions I have had cause to laugh at what is now a tiresome and adolescent excuse. Many private sellers will insist that their cars have full service histories usually denoted by the acroynm F.S.H which some people apparently believe means they can be trusted. Probe a little further and sometimes what the F.S.H actually requires is for the purchaser to take a leap of faith as the service record does not appear on paper but the seller can vouch for its authenticity. Usually the story goes that the car was serviced by a local mechanic who can change a timing belt but apparently can’t produce a receipt or even attest to the work having been done by simply stamping the service book. From here, if the&nbsp; seller is really brazen, they will plainly state that the mechanic does not own a stamp. At this point if you have not walked away from the sale then you can’t very well complain when things go wrong. If he/she is a little more inventive they might even go so far as to offer a written note from the mechanic stating all work has been carried out if one is so required. Unfortunately for far too many of you, this suffices. A hand written post-it with oil on the edges with the words “oil, air filter, brake pads 21/05/2012” assuages any doubts that the car has been given nothing other than a clean bill of health. These are the unexacting standards many purchasers are willing to apply to car purchasing and perhaps it is no wonder therefore that vehicles do not receive the treatment they require. Another shortcoming is to purchase a car with no history whatsoever and then deem this as a just excuse for not correcting the trend. Some people even purchase vehicles without the service book being present altogether. This is what you must contend with when you decide to purchase outside of a main or independent dealership.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><br /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify">Lastly, and in my own particular area of focus, the trade in allowance of vehicles with a limited, hazy or incomplete service record may suffer to a greater extent than the cost of a routine service. Uncertainty breeds caution and motor dealers are operating on such tight margins that every consideration is necessarily having to be scrutinized when a car is being traded in. It is entirely feasible that a service, two tyres, brake pads and a some minor body work could command a price tag of circa €1,000. This does not mean that the dealer will need to charge €1,000 more when the car comes to be sold. Market values are not dictated in this way. Instead the dealer will start at the end and firstly ascertain what they think the car being traded in can be sold for. Then they subtract profit, servicing and any other charge applicable to the situation. If your car requires more work then you will be given a lower price. And the more wooly the history of your car the more cautious a dealer will be to the extent that a car with a history to your ownership but none since might be worth up to €500 less than one with a service record which might only have cost €200 to keep unblemished. If finances allow for the car to receive even the most basic of services, its is surely better to commit to maintaining a flawless service record than one punctuated with lengthy gaps.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><br /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><br /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align:justify">At the time of compiling research for this essay, The Society of The Irish Motor Industry launched a campaign aimed at promoting the importance of prudent vehicle maintenance details of which can be found here.</p>  <div style="text-align:justify"><br /></div>', '<p>Unless you are a particularly discerning motorist, the likelihood is that you are unable to distinguish the performance of a properly or indeed recently serviced vehicle from one that hasn’t had&nbsp;</p>', '2012-05-21', '1337614911.jpeg', '108'),
(107, 'New Features', 13, 1, 1, 'The site has only been live for one month and already we have some exciting new features to announce.<div><br /></div><div>Users will now be able to change their passwords by clicking "My Account" above the Logout button.<div><br /></div><div>Our Mileage Adjustment Calculator now has a range of up to 50,000km''s over the average mileage and 40,000km''s below the&nbsp;mileage stated. What''s more - we haven''t had to sacrifice any accuracy to values in order to achieve this. Go on, give it a go.</div></div><div><br /></div><div>.PDF printouts are now available for each car. When a vehicle is selected, you will now notice a pdf logo in the blue box underneath the values. Simply select this and a pdf printout should appear in a separate window. Here you can save, email or print the page depending on your requirements.</div><div><br /></div><div>These neat features are just a few&nbsp;of the great additions to the site we have been working on, some of which came from you the user. So if you have an idea on how to improve our service to you, simply email us on carguide@mtp.ie</div><div><br /></div>', 'The site has only been live for one month and already we have some exciting new features to announce', '2012-04-25', '1335358564.jpeg', '107'),
(109, 'Landcruiser: A Case Study', 11, 1, 1, '<div style="width:425px" id="__ss_13045683"><strong style="display:block;margin:12px 0 4px"><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/aidotimmo/landcruiser-case-study" title="Landcruiser case study">Landcruiser case study</a></strong><object id="__sse13045683" width="425" height="355" classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0">\r\n</object>\r\n<div style="padding:5px 0 12px">View more <a href="http://www.slideshare.net/">presentations</a> from <a href="http://www.slideshare.net/aidotimmo">aidotimmo</a>.</div></div>', '<span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Click "Read more" and follow the link to view the case study.</span>', '2012-05-23', '1337784851.jpeg', '109'),
(110, 'New mileage calculator', 10, 1, 1, '<span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">We are proud to announce the launch of our updated mileage calculator which allows the user to generate an even more accurate value for each specific vehicle based on the exact odometer reading.</span><div><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Log in to try it for yourself.</span></div><div><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif"><br /></span></div><div><div><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="http://thecarguide.files.wordpress.com/2012/07/onlineshotcircled.jpg" style="border:0px  #000000;width:500px;height:378px;vertical-align:baseline" /></span>  </div></div>', '<span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">We are proud to announce the launch of our updated mileage calculator which allows the user to generate an even more accurate value for each specific vehicle based on the exact odometer reading. Log in to try it for yourself.</span>', '2012-07-17', '1342519268.jpeg', '110'),
(111, 'Instructional video: Using new mileage calculator', 7, 1, 1, '<span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">We have uploaded this walkthrough to explain how to use our new features. Click "Read more" to view the video.</span><div><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif"><br /></span></div><div><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif"><br /></span></div>\r\n<iframe width="480" height="360" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/E4Chcz2vHvw" frameborder="0"></iframe>', '<span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">We have uploaded this walkthrough to explain how to use our new features. Click "Read more" to view the video.</span>', '2012-07-17', '1343992558.jpeg', '111'),
(112, 'July Market Analysis', 9, 1, 1, 'Conducting research visits&nbsp;with&nbsp;an elevated intensity this year has&nbsp;provided&nbsp;the team at Motor Trade Publishers with a cocktail of insightful feedback.Click "Read more" to watch the video.\r\n<iframe width="480" height="360" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/tstvkWOcTdI" frameborder="0"></iframe>', 'Conducting research visits&nbsp;with&nbsp;an elevated intensity this year has&nbsp;provided&nbsp;the team at Motor Trade Publishers with a cocktail of insightful feedback. Click "Read more" to watch the video. Enjoy.', '2012-07-18', '1342606394.jpeg', '112'),
(114, 'November Editorial', 6, 1, 1, '<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">While speculation concerning the proposed changes to motor tax has emerged there is still far too much business to be conducted in the interim. The end of year provides a chance for our research to focus more heavily on the likely New Year values of vehicles. To this end we attempt to ease the transition from one year to another by taking heavier falls at the tail end of the year. For many vehicles however, the fall from October to January seems likely to be a fraction of what it has typically been, such is the scarcity of stock.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Throughout this year our research results have largely been characterized by almost complete agreement among dealers within every brand. However, with New Year looming some traditionalists maintain that vehicles must fall quite heavily in order for the returning hire drive vehicles to logically be placed. This school of thought holds that current year used vehicles necessarily depress one year old values to such a point that there might even be some additional effects on 2 year old vehicles.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Others maintain that stock is so scarce that the returning fleet will have little effect once they have been sold off and we again find that one and two year old vehicle’s are highly sought after. This camp view January values as being almost as highly performing as October prices with only nominal falls forecasted. Our analysis finds that both sides are correct depending on the vehicle type. Many cars have not fallen by much this year. The cost of change in like for like models has narrowed in some cases to less than €2,000 per year which represents extremely good value for money. There is certainly room for some models to take a moderate fall and still retain excellent profit potential.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">November&nbsp;also signifies the publication of the penultimate issue of The Light Commercial and Four Wheel Drive Guide. Here the changes in price are more pronounced. Some large SUV’s are still grappling to reduce their CO2 values and used prices are suffering as a result. Mid size SUV’s too have found the going tough this year and as cross overs emerge more frequently this segment will find it hard to attract customers unless they are keenly priced. Small and medium panel vans are thriving. Despite some new price incentives, larger vans still appeal to very specific customers and sales remain very low.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Values for&nbsp;November&nbsp;have fallen by&nbsp;<em><strong>(VALUE RESERVED FOR SUBSCRIBERS ONLY)</strong>&nbsp;</em>but there are still many individual models that require strict attention to ensure they are properly positioned alongside their competitors. The gaps in prices between family hatch backs and saloons have narrowed greatly as many opt to downsize one or both cars in the family. This, among with other balances and comparisons will continue to predominate our research as we endeavor to ensure values for January most accurately represent the true market value.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif"><br /></p>', '<span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">While speculation concerning the proposed changes to motor tax has emerged there is still far too much business to be conducted in the interim. &nbsp;<span style="font-weight:bold">PRESS READ MORE TO SEE FULL VERSION.</span></span>', '2012-11-19', '1353329848.jpeg', '114'),
(113, 'The Motor Trade Publishers Method', 5, 1, 1, '<span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">On July 5th, our senior research analyst Aidan Timmons presented a comprehensive overview of the methods employed by Motor Trade Publishers in establishing vehicle values. Here is an abbreviated version of that discussion.</span><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif"></span><div><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif"><br /></span></div><div><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif"><br /></span></div>\r\n<iframe width="480" height="360" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/7fzbdc_Emr8" frameborder="0"></iframe>', '<span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">On July 5th, our senior research analyst Aidan Timmons presented a comprehensive overview of the methods employed by Motor Trade Publishers in establishing vehicle values. Here is an abbreviated version of that discussion.</span>   <div><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif"><br /></span></div><div><span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Click "Read more" to see the video.</span></div>', '2012-07-26', '1343992517.png', '113'),
(115, 'October Editorial', 8, 1, 1, '<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">The motor trade does not cease to amaze and this month in particular copper fastens the notion that expecting the unexpected is the best approach when it comes to used car values. At the time of going to print the demand for returning fleet vehicles had yet to be established though the prevailing consensus among those we researched with was that budgetary constraints felt by the customer means that attractive finance packages and deal sweeteners such as extended warranties or free servicing might now be required to attract customers en masse.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">We are seeing more than ever, reliance by some dealers to value stock they might not be frequently familiar with by comparing similar models for sale online. Whilst we have remained fairly tight lipped on the matter, the complexity and changeability of the motor trade now merits some words in response.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Firstly, the values contained herewith and on our website&nbsp;<a href="http://www.mtp.ie/">www.mtp.ie</a>&nbsp;and ‘thecarguide’ app for iPhone are direct results of analysing hundreds of individual values obtained from within the motor trade. Indeed many readers or your colleagues might be personally responsible for having influenced the guide book at a particular point in the year. There can be little doubt then, that the values in the guide book are the results of considering yours and your peers’ assessment of the market.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">This is instrumental when it comes to trusting the validity of The Car Sales Guide values. We strip bear the “wants” and the “would likes” and focus directly on actual prices. Doubtless there is anyone who does not see the distinction between an asking price and a selling price yet it can sometimes transpire that the method of valuing online is afforded more credibility than it duly deserves.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Our research in September yielded some startling results which again throws the traditional idea of only downwardly readjusting values at this point in the year somewhat out the window. Some vehicle’s prices have fallen only very marginally from their start of year figures and one would assume that with the year’s end looming that values should now begin to drop more rapidly. There are vehicles which conform to this but there are many besides whose values for the month have remained relatively untouched and even cases where residuals have increased.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Considering such a mixed market atmosphere a general fall of circa<strong>&nbsp;[values reserved for subscribers only]</strong>&nbsp;only serves to satisfy a portion of the vehicles in the guide book. Others (predominantly larger engine petrol models or even executive diesels) have required stronger price restructuring and where hire drive vehicles have returned in greater numbers thus potentially straining one year values, we will continue to closely monitor the performance of vehicles in this segment. Our research for the remaining months will switch to January values and we invite all dealers to contact us on&nbsp;<a href="mailto:carguide@mtp.ie">carguide@mtp.ie</a>&nbsp;should they wish to submit their thoughts on how the market is likely to progress.</p><p><br /></p>', '<span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">The motor trade does not cease to amaze and this month in particular copper fastens the notion that expecting the unexpected is the best approach when it comes to used car values.<span style="font-weight:bold"> CLICK READ MORE TO SEE FULL VERSION</span>&nbsp;</span>', '2012-11-19', '1353330096.jpeg', '115'),
(116, 'Editorial January 2013', 4, 1, 1, '.<p>The implications of the measures introduced in Budget 2013 are already having a profound effect on the residual values for many vehicles. The increase in Vehicle Registration Tax means that the cost of some new cars will rise by more than €3,000 from their pre-budget position. It is impossible to ignore the obvious impact to used vehicle values that an increase such as this will extol, primarily where one and two year old vehicles are concerned. It is harder still to underestimate the effects of the continuing scarcity of stock of quality used cars. The result is a January 2013 Car Sales Guide that for many vehicles, displays a year on year value that greatly outperforms that of 12 months ago.</p><p>The order book for January was a lot emptier than many would prefer as we drew a close to 2012 so doubtless there is anyone who is not anxious about the uptake in the first few months of this year. Again, the rise in VRT means that most new cars have become dearer with only an exceptional few who have managed to counter the increase with a reduction in CO2, which has a stabilizing effect on the new price. Others have absorbed the increase or simply reduced the new price but they are in a minority. Price increases for new cars have further implications on the used car market as dealers now thread a very fine line between offering enough to the customer for their trade-in but not too much so as to alienate the used car buyer who might not be able to afford the now higher priced vehicle.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Light Commercial and Four Wheel Drive Guide was one of the most difficult to produce in recent memory. Motor tax confuses the balance between model years to the extent that some dealers maintain that 2009 registered vehicles with high tax will make only a negligible amount above the equivalent 2008 model. Fresh models from newly emerged product ranges have become increasingly popular and their values are amongst the highest residual percentages in the guide book. For dealers who are fortunate enough to have ready access to small vans, good profit margins can be achieved such is their desirability by a growing client base who are not only downsizing but also in more immediate need of changing their vehicle. For these reasons values for small vans remain closely aligned to their end of year positions.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This year will also herald the introduction of the double registration plate system. The advocates for such a system are unwavering in their optimism about the positive effects of spreading the new car sales market throughout the year. Indeed if the mechanism has even only a very slight positive effect it will be worth it. Although, it should be noted that we might not experience the full potential of this system until there is greater economic stability. Moreover, the system brings with it some inherent timing issues with returning hire drive vehicles and whether used values should be differentiated by registration plate. In any case, we will continue to monitor the performance of the system and hope to report on its success.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Car Sales Guide this month shows year on year values for many models to be higher than they were at the start of 2012. An assessment of some models against their equivalent yearly values in January of 2012 shows an increase in residuals by as much as 3%-7%. The net result is that the yearly depreciation for many vehicles is minimal and the price gap between each year grows narrower still. I would like to take this opportunity to wish everybody the very best wishes for successful and prosperous trading throughout all of 2013.</p><p>Aidan Timmons</p>', 'The implications of the measures introduced in Budget 2013 are already having a profound effect on the residual values for many vehicles. The increase in Vehicle Registration Tax means that the cost of some new cars will rise by more than €3,000 from their pre-budget position', '2013-01-07', '1357557408.jpeg', '116'),
(119, 'Editorial February 2013', 2, 1, 1, '<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif;color:#009999;text-align:center"><span style="font-weight:bold;font-size:large">Editorial: Precarious start to 2013</span></p><h2></h2><br /><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">The\r\nyear has begun with an all too familiar feeling that the motor trade is again\r\nbracing itself for a particularly difficult period ahead. At the time of going\r\nto print, the 20 day new car registration figures from the SIMI reveal that new\r\ncar sales are not operating at anything like the rate that the market requires\r\nif it is to ensure a healthy supply of used cars for future trading. A brief\r\nglimpse at the number of used imports in December 2012 provides further\r\nemphasis of the appetite of customers for 2009, 2010 and 2011 registered cars.\r\nHowever, what it also points to is the budget that dealers are willing to\r\nstretch to keep their forecourts appropriately stocked.</p>\r\n<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">&nbsp;This\r\nmonth’s Guide includes values for 2012 registered vehicles. Our values are used\r\nwithin the finance and insurance sectors and so as well as obtaining quality\r\ninformation directly from dealers we also cross check values with the requests that\r\ncome through corporate channels. In almost every query put to us, our proposed\r\nvalue for one year old vehicles was suitably close to that being sought for\r\nfinance. This raises one very important point concerning finance, which is that\r\nit appears the availability of credit might no longer be a persistent barrier\r\nto sales. Perhaps the manufacturer backed finance packages has meant that\r\npillar banks are under less strain to fulfill most of the finance deals.</p>\r\n<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">&nbsp;It was\r\nspeculated that the increase in new car prices because of the change to VRT\r\nwould cause a rise in used car values to maintain an attractive cost-to-change\r\nfor new car customers. We have not yet heard of any cars performing higher than\r\nthey did at the end of 2012 but for the most part the used car market is\r\nperforming excellently. Petrol values for desirable models with acceptable motor\r\ntax rates are not providing the issues to dealers that they have done in\r\nprevious years. And while stock remains scarce, thankfully enough of what is\r\ncoming back to the market is deemed saleable and what is more important,\r\nprofitable.</p>\r\n<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">&nbsp;The\r\nquestion of whether or not the dual registration plate will have any positive\r\neffect on new car sales remains to be seen. It is our opinion that broader\r\neconomic forces have a greater impact on retail sales figures than any\r\nstructural change to registrations. Either way, what can be said with a better\r\ndegree of certainty is that stock will likely remain scarce this year, which\r\nshould help to bolster residual values. More and more we are hearing from\r\ndealers of the type of stock that they are now willing to retail which extends\r\nfrom older cars in clean condition to newer high mileage examples that\r\nrepresent value for money.</p>\r\n<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">&nbsp;The\r\nCar Sales Guide this month is about consolidating the values that appeared in\r\nthe January Guide. Traditionally, it is not until March that the used car\r\nmarket begins to readjust values more noticeably. When this does happen we will\r\nhave already compiled the first wave of our field research so that we are in a\r\nposition to accurately reflect emerging patterns in real time.&nbsp;</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Aidan Timmons</p>', '<span style="font-size:medium;font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">The year has begun with an all too familiar feeling that the motor trade is again bracing itself for a particularly difficult period ahead.</span>', '2013-01-31', '1359624087.jpeg', '119'),
(118, 'The Motor Trade Publishers Method', 3, 0, 1, '<img src="pictures/client/MethodInfographV7.png" style="width:600px;height:2400px" title="The Key to Accuracy" />', '', '2013-01-07', '1357573786.png', '118'),
(120, 'Editorial March 2013', 1, 1, 1, '<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">It seems that the motor trade has grown accustomed to an under-performing new car sales environment so dealers are resolutely seeking to sustain business by maximizing the profitability of their used stock. Acknowledging the lack of appropriate used cars is a well beaten drum at this stage and this months Car Sales Guide reflects dealers’ reluctance to take values back when the cost of replacing stock becomes an increasingly more difficult and expensive undertaking. Comparing February’s guide book to this edition shows that some eminently popular models have even increased in value where projected New Year residuals proved to be aiming a little low.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">This is not an all-together unusual development in the industry. In some cases it is a reaction to a pronounced scarcity of a particular model. In other situations it is simply an increased appetite of customers for a particular model and a willingness to pay stronger prices for the right car. Where this month’s guide book differs from previous issues is that, save some larger petrol models with high motor tax rates, the almost complete stabilization of values is undeniable. It is a used car market that is punctuated with new cars and not .</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Cumulative new car sales figures tell only part of the story and there is positivity to be found in emerging brands whose model range has grown to offer competitive products in more than one segment. The effect these cars have on the wider market is to attract some customers out of their comfort zones and into a relatively untested brand. Although, ultimately deals may only be achieved if the trade-in value of the bigger brand is considered attractive. It will be interesting to see if this results in a wider range of used models on forecourts rather than the more conservative approach that has been evident in recent times. It also makes The Car Sales Guide an ever-relevant tool to assess products not seen for some time or even at all.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">The values in the guide for March are&nbsp;<strong>(details of values reserved for subscribers only)</strong>. Obviously there will be vehicles whose scarcity might be considered a blessing. These vehicles are very few in numbers but we have still ensured that normal monthly falls apply nonetheless. March is habitually a short working month for the motor trade with various holidays and sporting events primed to disrupt business but unlike previous years, the market is holding so firm that it would take more than a hiccup in activity to drastically affect used vehicle values.</p><p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">Aidan Timmons</p>', 'It seems that the motor trade has grown accustomed to an under-performing new car sales environment so dealers are resolutely seeking to sustain business by maximizing the profitability of their used stock.', '2013-03-01', '1362162664.jpeg', '120'),
(123, 'Editorial June 2013', 0, 1, 1, '<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">June\r\nsignifies the final month for the first of two registration plates under the\r\nnew system and is also traditionally the time when new car sales stagnate. The\r\nperformance of used car values so far this year has been nothing short of\r\nastonishing. Since January the majority of vehicles in The Car Sales Guide have\r\neither experienced a shoring up of values or a consolidation of strong early\r\nyear positions. Continuing the trend indefinitely was never a real\r\nconsideration and values had to fall at some stage so it is perhaps no surprise\r\nthen that this has occurred in the immediacy before a change in registration\r\nplate.</p>\r\n<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">&nbsp;There is\r\nlittle expectation for this month’s new car sales to be anything other than\r\nminimal. Cognizant of the new plate, customers might decide to delay taking\r\ndelivery of their new car until July. Should this transpire, it will have the\r\neffect of delaying the return of vehicles being traded in until at least next\r\nmonth. Despite this contributing to a shortage of used stock, our research\r\nnecessitates that we readjust some values downwards. It should be clarified\r\nthat while this months Guide contains a greater fall in values over previous\r\nmonths that the drop comes from a much higher position than expected, with some\r\nvehicles values having enjoyed a long period of consistent upward revision.</p>\r\n<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">The\r\nsegment most notably affected by the depreciation in values this month is the\r\nfamily saloon segment and most significantly fresh used models within it. The\r\npremium in value held by these cars over their hatchback alternatives is\r\nlessening despite the new price for some saloon models increasing. Until now,\r\nthere had been no suggestions that imports, which plugged gaps in the used car\r\nmarket this year, were having an undesirable effect on residual values.\r\nHowever, our most recent research hints to some isolated circumstances in which\r\nvalues are distorted owing to a greater level of imports for some models. We\r\nwill continue to monitor this situation and whether imports have a more far\r\nreaching effect as the year progresses.</p>\r\n<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">We\r\nreceive numerous queries concerning the approach The Car Sales Guide will take\r\nin differentiating values for 131 and 132 registered vehicles. In previous\r\neditorials we have alluded to the potential impacts on current year demo and\r\npre-registered stock that carries over to another registration period but we\r\nare not in the business of pre-empting a situation as delicate as this one. Opinions\r\non what the likely impact on values will be divide the motor trade but we\r\nremain impartial and aware that anything is possible, including there being no\r\ndifference between values whatsoever. Perhaps odometer readings might well be\r\nthe only cause for a discernible difference in values. In any case, we will\r\nensure our values accurately reflect market conditions.</p>\r\n<p style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">The Car\r\nSales Guide this month represents a downward revision in the order of 1% for\r\nmany models which do not require either stricter depreciative readjustments or\r\ncontinuing upward revisions. Some cars do conform to the latter and but in many\r\nof these cases the firming of values might only apply to some model years where\r\nthere is increased scarcity or where petrol values have begun to narrow the gap\r\nto their diesel counterparts.</p>', '<span style="font-family:helvetica, sans-serif">June signifies the final month for the first of two registration plates under the new system and is also traditionally the time when new car sales stagnate.&nbsp;</span>', '2013-06-06', '1370530227.jpeg', '123');
