(82, 59, 'downloads', 'Blog', 'Downloads', 'Blog Articles', 'Blog', 'Download guide files values prices car Ireland ', '1', '7', NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, '<p><span style="font-weight:bold;font-family:helvetica, sans-serif;color:#339999;font-size:x-large" class="&lt;img src=" http:="" mtp.ie="" assets="" cb833906="" images="" pixel.gif"="" title="" rel="media5624875405337662" width="150" height="100">The Car Sales Guide Editorials and Blog Posts</span></p><div><strong>Each month our editorial concentrates on the market performance of used cars. We regularly provide additional commentary on the motor trade. Here is a sample of the&nbsp;catalogue of what has been published since the inception of this website. For a comprehensive list please visit <a href="http://thecarguide.wordpress.com/">www.thecarguide.wordpress.com</a></strong></div><div><strong><br /></strong></div><div><strong><br /></strong></div><div><h2><strong style="color:#339999">The "estate" we''re in</strong></h2><p>It seems like an eternity ago that credit was free flowing and the decision to upgrade your car every couple of years was almost a given. After all, in the climate that existed at the time it made perfect sense. Now however, many find a petrol model SUV parked in the driveway and a real dilemma on their hands when it comes to deciding on a replacement. You see, there really isn’t any issue with the SUV body shape other than it may be a little cumbersome in city traffic or around shopping centre car parks but the space and comfort it affords far outweighs either of those niggles. The issue is the usual complaint amongst owners today, and that is they don’t want a petrol vehicle anymore. So why don’t these people just go and buy a diesel SUV I hear you say. Well it isn’t as straightforward as you might think.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Firstly, many SUV diesel models come in what we like to consider “large engine sizes”, which used to mean 2.5 and 3.0 litres but with the advent of the high output, small diesel engine now it means anything above a 2.0 litre. And this is compounded by Kia and Hyundai’s recent launch of the Sportage and iX35 respectively. In fact, Hyundai had released the iX35 in its 2.0 guise here first but dealers acknowledge that the 1.7 will certainly outsell its larger counterpart. Even Range Rover have lumped a 2.2 diesel heart into its new Evoque. This is nothing new as it already features in its Freelander range, but the desire to spread the same smaller engine across its range is testament to the desire of manufacturers to not only reduce CO2 emissions but also engine capacity. Basically, in both respects the smaller the number, the better.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>So, we have a family with a petrol model SUV looking to change and not being able to afford the new smaller diesel engine models and have no interest in anything above a 2.0 diesel. Well there is hope on the horizon as a surprising feature of the post VRT restructuring debacle has been the resurgence of a dormant player in the market – the humble estate. Typically considered as a “sales reps” car, the estates of old bore no resemblance to their better looking saloon cousins. Boxy, awkward and a little too bland, they were almost like driving the epitome of mundane. However, on closer inspection the requirements of a sales rep are shared by many potential buyers who seek a comfortable, economical, affordable, spacious and refined vehicle.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Marketing departments the world over have seized the opportunity to reinvent these vehicles by rebranding them as “Crosswagon” or “Tourer” or my personal favourite “Sportback”. Somehow this makes them sound sportier or more exclusive and had they simply just renamed the vehicles I would contest their validity however, they have backed up their new titles with aesthetically beautiful bodywork. Indeed some estates (I’m a purist so forgive me for sticking with the original term) are far superior in the looks department than their previously more handsome saloon brothers.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Furthermore the estate has remained practical and the designers have obviously spent thousands of thumb bleeding hours mastering Tetris on their old Nintendo Gameboys and studying IKEA catalogues as the size of the average estate has remained much the same but with a greater emphasis on internal storage space. Not only that, but estates come in the same engine sizes as their saloon equivalents. They don’t tend to have drastically higher CO2 levels either so provided the saloon model is well down the spectrum, customers can expect affordable road tax rates also. It is the ultimate utilitarian vehicle in today’s modern Ireland where the SUV has whetted our appetite for large family transport but which is now struggling to offer up the same diverse selection found in the estate segment.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I never joined in on the SUV-bashing crusade for a number of reasons and I am not about to now either. Many anti-SUV protagonists must have been cursing under their breath when the treacherous conditions last winter exposed many of the weaknesses of “regular” vehicles. And I don’t for a second buy the argument that because they pollute more they should be penalized through taxes when the average SUV driver may cover far less mileage than a saloon or hatchback owner. But, what I am in favour of is a balanced approach to purchasing new and used vehicles and if truth be told, there are many among us who blatantly and wrongly ignored the plucky estate in favour of the SUV.</p><strong><br /></strong></div><div><strong><br /></strong></div><div><strong><br /></strong></div><h2><span style="color:#339999">The year of the used car: 2012 in review</span><br /><strong></strong></h2><div><p>The used car market has long been the lifeblood of the motor trade in Ireland but since 2009 it’s place as the protagonist has become increasingly more established. New car sales in January 2012 got off to yet another sluggish start though many distributors shrewdly opted not to incur the rise in VAT outlined in December 2011′s budget. This had the effect of somewhat safeguarding against what is fast becoming something of a stock crisis for dealers. With lower than preferred new car sales the trade are having to find alternative methods of satisfying demand; the most noticeable being the willingness to deal in older stock or vehicles with higher mileage or both.</p><p>As the year progressed into the Spring I reported on some resurging petrol models whose residual values had suffered more heavily during the downturn than their diesel counterparts. The cavernous gap that divided the two fuel types used values meant that customers were finally beginning to see the merit in purchasing a petrol car despite having to shoulder the extra cost at the pumps and when taxing the car. (I wrote an article concering the sensibility in purchasing a petrol vehicle some years ago but which remained pertinent during the period after the article was published – a link is found&nbsp;<a href="http://wp.me/p1UVxN-3">here</a>).</p><p><strong></strong></p><blockquote><p><strong>"The cavernous gap that divided the two fuel types used values meant that customers were finally beginning to see the merit in purchasing a petrol car"</strong></p></blockquote><br /><p>Another tough year was momentarily interrupted by great positivity and belief as our national football team contested the Euro 2012 championships in Poland. The excitement soon waned and we were left facing business in the Autumn with a sour taste in our mouths. Autumn brought the returning hire drive fleet to the market and for a few weeks the values of 2011 stock suffered as incentives prevailed on present year stock. Dealers quickly arrested the slide by selling off the stock they had quickly and then holding out for higher prices on their remaining stock, doubtlessly conscious that once the used car sells it is near impossible to replace it with a like model at such a late stage in the year or indeed at a reasonable price. This fortitude proved sensible as values towards the end of this year held firm and some dealers reported a return of customer footfall to showrooms – a noticeably lacking feature of previous years.</p><p><strong></strong></p><blockquote><p><strong>"<span style="font-style: italic; font-family: ''times new roman'', times, serif; font-size: large; color: rgb(0, 153, 153);" class="&lt;img src=" http:="" mtp.ie="" assets="" cb833906="" images="" pixel.gif"="" title="pictures/client/MethodInfographV7.png" rel="media6235363169107586" width="150" height="100">conscious that once the used car sells it is near impossible to replace it with a like model at such a late stage in the year or indeed at a reasonable price</span>"</strong></p></blockquote>  <br /><br /><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong>The importance of this can hardly be overstated when we consider the measures which will affect the motor trade and were outlined in Budget 2013. Many new cars will incur an increase of circa €500-€1,000. For those not in the motor trade, “the cost to change” is the shortfall between the price being offered for the car that the customer is trading in and the one they are buying. Essentially, with new vehicle prices increasing in 2013 dealers have a crucial decision to make concerning a customer’s cost to change. They can either request the customer shoulder the increased disparity between the trade in and the new car or they offer the customer more money than they would have done previously, thereby maintaining the same monetary gap between the new car and the trade in. Many dealers have informed me that they will choose the latter. This has obvious implications on used car values in 2013 and so we might see an even stronger year for these cars next year than we saw throughout the last 12 months.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong></strong></p><p><strong><strong></strong></strong></p><br /><blockquote>"<span style="font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;font-family:''times new roman'', times, serif;font-size:large;color:rgb(0, 153, 153)" class="&lt;img src= &lt;img src=" http:="" mtp.ie="" assets="" cb833906="" images="" pixel.gif"="" title="pictures/client/MethodInfographV7.png" rel="media2672147883567959" width="150" height="100"> <img src="http://www.mtp.ie/assets/cb833906/images/pixel.gif" rel="media7940030333120376" width="150" height="100" />" http:="" mtp.ie="" assets="" cb833906="" images="" pixel.gif"="" title="pictures/client/MethodInfographV7.png" rel="media06951571139506996" width="150" height="100"&gt;Essentially, with new vehicle prices increasing in 2013 dealers have a crucial decision to make concerning a customer’s cost to change</span>"</blockquote><br /><br /><br /><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong>I am eminently aware that this article concerns the events in 2012 but I would be remiss not to expand somewhat on that previous and significant point and look towards 2013 for a moment. I began this review by highlighting the used car market’s significance to the motor trade and indeed to customers who can not afford a new car (or who don’t see the merit in buying one) but I can go further by saying that used car values should hold tremendously strong in 2013. Scarcity of supply is just one key element but the rise in VRT does not just impact on the new car. As I alluded to in the previous paragraph, motor dealers will attempt to keep the cost to change for each customer closely aligned to what they were at the start of 2012.</strong></p>\r\n<p>A simple mathematical example will serve to better illustrate the point:</p><p>Car A is traded in against Car B. Pre-Budget 2013 Car A costs €25,000. Car B is being traded against this and an allowance of €15,000 is afforded to the customer. The cost to change the vehicle is therefore €10,000.</p><p>Post Budget 2013 Car A costs €26,000.</p><p>In order for the “cost to change” to remain identical to the previous example (or for instance a previous transaction 12 months previously), Car B must attract an allowance of €16,000.</p><p>The dealer now must seek a higher price for Car B than they would previously have done. The used car’s value has risen or at the very least remained virtually unchanged (barring external factors such as the age of the vehicle, it’s salability, scarcity of supply and other extraneous implications). Therefore, the rise in VRT in Budget 2013, might not only impact on the new car buyer but it may effect the used car buyer too. The customer who wishes to buy Car B now needs to pay €1,000 more than they would have had the new price not increased (unless of course they are also granted more money for their trade in). It might transpire that the increase will either be absorbed by the dealer, the new customer, used customer or a combination of all three but regardless the result is a used car market that is primed to thrive even more in 2013 than it did in 2012. In fact, my research shows that values for January 2013 are between 3%-7% greater than January 2012. This is surely a sign of the strength of the motor trade and the constantly growing popularity of used cars.</p><p>2012 will also be remembered for its registration plate. Due to a change in the method of identifying vehicles in Ireland from January 2013 onwards by signifying the first half of the year with an extra “1″ after the first two digits ie: 131 D 1234 and a “2″ from July onwards ie: 132 D 4567, 2012 is the last time that two digits representing the year will be used. My post-budget skepticism of the effectiveness of this system are documented&nbsp;<a href="http://wp.me/p1UVxN-4w">here</a>, though suffice it to say that the framework requires a change in economic circumstances and possibly a revision of when the budget is announced in order for it to have the full desired effect on new car sales.</p><p>Personally, the previous twelve months have been fruitful from a professional perspective. For Motor Trade Publishers, our new&nbsp;<a href="http://www.mtp.ie/">website</a>&nbsp;meant that we can now provide our values to a wider audience and our mileage adjustment calculator is the most accurate on the market. We combined our expertise with the incredibly talented people at&nbsp;<a href="http://www.mywheels.ie/">MyWheels</a>&nbsp;to provide the market with used car history checks and vehicle values in the same package. I also had the fantastic opportunity to present a motoring television program. “Driving Seat” aired on TV3 and the five episodes comprised a wonderful cocktail of real-world vehicle reviews and Irish success stories. I have thanked those who went to such Herculean efforts to make the show a success and I extend that gratification to those of you who watched the show and supported me throughout it’s run. Expect to see more reviews in one shape or form next year.</p><p>The used car market is an immensely difficult one to assess but I relish the opportunity to do it all again next year. I wish all of Motor Trade Publishers’ subscribers and the readers of this blog a very happy New Year and I look forward to interacting with you in 2013.</p><p>Aidan</p>  <br /></div><div><strong><br /></strong></div><h2><strong>Budget 2013 and the motor trade</strong></h2><div><strong><p>The government have compounded the shortcomings of the much maligned motor tax system by opting not to restructure the framework in it’s entirety but rather to increase Vehicle Registration Tax and motor tax for lower CO2 emitting vehicles. The administration’s move comes off the back of negotiations with parties from within the motor trade but will likely be considered by those groups as a failure to recognise the seriousness of the damage the recession is causing to employment in that sector.</p><p>The details outlined in Budget 2013 make provision for the sub-categorisation of the two lowest bands of&nbsp; VRT, A and B. 92%<a href="http://thecarguide.wordpress.com/Documents%20and%20Settings/ATimmons/Desktop/MotorTax2013AidanTimmons.doc#_ftn1">[1]</a>&nbsp;of all new vehicles sold in Ireland up to the end of November of this year reside in bands A and B with the split weighted more heavily in the lowest category where VRT is just 14%. The motor tax system will now feature new bands which punctuate the lowest categories, namely; &nbsp;A1, A2, A3 A4, between bands A and B and between categories B and C, B1 and B2. Each sub band represents increments of 1% so that vehicles in band A1 will attract VRT liability of 14% whilst band A3 will be subject to 16% VRT.</p><p>Band B2, which used be captured by the original system’s Band B, sees VRT for vehicles with 131-140g CO2/km jump from 16% to 19%. The move will have a net monetary effect of increasing some mainstream models by as much as €500 to €1500. The effects on new car sales will likely be detrimental with some analysts pointing to a reduction in new car registrations of between 5% and 8% for 2013, though these figures also take into consideration various other economic forces. The market will register around 80,000 new cars this year which represents a fall of 57% from the figure posted in 2007. At these levels motor dealers increasingly seek to sustain business by concentrating on used cars. However, with dwindling levels of available stock the likelihood is that more closures and job losses will be incurred.</p><p>Minister Noonan confirmed that the registration system for new vehicles will be split to separate the first and second halves of the year; a new 3 digit registration identifier will commence from January 1<sup>st</sup>&nbsp;and will appear as 131 and 132 respectively. Minister Noonan affirmed that this scheme will “incentivise a more year round motor market” though the increases in new vehicle prices and the timing of the second registration plate which will coincide with returning hire drive vehicles could render the positive impacts of this measure as entirely negligible.</p><p>Motorists have escaped a rise in excise duty on petrol and diesel which is a surprising but doubtlessly encouraging move by the Minister for Finance. The cost of motoring has escalated at an alarming rate which has resulted in over 50% of the average cost of a litre of fuel being attributable to taxes<a href="http://thecarguide.wordpress.com/Documents%20and%20Settings/ATimmons/Desktop/MotorTax2013AidanTimmons.doc#_ftn2">[2]</a>.</p><p>Finally, motor tax has again proved a reliable source from which the government can extract more revenue. Vehicles registered prior to 2008 and therefore subject to motor tax based on their engine size will be subject to increases from €14 for vehicles under 1,000 cc to as much as €126 for the largest engine capacity vehicles. Mainly though, 1.4 and 1.6 litre vehicles will incur an additional yearly charge of between €27 and €38. For lower CO2 emitting vehicles purchased from 2008 onwards the yearly increase begins at just €10 for those now in Band A1 and an extra €92 for those in Band G. This results in an average increase of €39 for vehicles falling within the scope of the present motor tax system.</p><p>The effects that these measures will have on the motor trade are yet to be determined but increasing motor tax and VRT in every budget in previous years previously has yet to yield a positive result. The motor trade faces an unenviable task of growing their market at a time when the costs involved with motoring are rising. The double registration system has been on the wish lists of some for many years though the arguments for its effectiveness will surely be watered down by the likely increase in new car prices as a result of increased VRT percentages. For full details of the increases to motor tax implemented in Budget 2013 please visit the link below.</p><p><a href="http://http//budget.gov.ie/Budgets/2013/Documents/Annex%20C%20-%20VRT%20and%20Motor%20Tax.pdf">http://budget.gov.ie/Budgets/2013/Documents/Annex%20C%20-%20VRT%20and%20Motor%20Tax.pdf</a></p><p>Aidan Timmons</p><p>Senior Research Analyst</p><p>Motor Trade Publishers</p><p><br /></p><p><strong>December Editorial</strong>  <br /></p><p><br /></p>\r\n<p>It has not been without enormous degrees of hard work and perseverance that we now find ourselves at the end of what was another challenging year for the motor trade. There are certainly enough reasons to be cautious about the coming year though it is important to remain resilient and look for the positives, however difficult that might sound.&nbsp; In the main, the standard and quality of the ever increasing range of products available has rarely been better. Service packs and car maintenance offers should mean used cars return in better condition too. And for some brands fortunate enough to avail of manufacturer backed finance offers, new car sales have an increased chance of being helped across the line.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To borrow a phrase used by some dealers we research with, used car values will be held through the turn of the year on a “case by case basis”. 2008, 2009 and 2010 registered diesel vehicles are among those whose values have fallen only nominally this year. With the prospect of an increase in VRT for most new cars, dealers have been quick to point that the customer’s cost to change will need to remain largely the same as it would have been without any increase in new price. The net result is that residual values for a selection of popular models are anticipated to hold steady into the New Year.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Forward orders however, have not been fulfilled at anything like the rate that some dealers would prefer. It seems that many prospective buyers have postponed their new car enquiries until Minister Noonan delivers the details of Budget 2013. This too, has the effect of encouraging some outlets to maintain projected January values close to end of year levels. The implications of yet another potentially poor year for new car sales weighs heavy on all of our minds not least because of the impact it will have on the availability of used stock in future years but also because the cost of importing vehicles from the UK has become a less profitable option.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Incentives on new cars from distributors abound again in the pre-January advertising campaigns. Just as it was the case last year, brands are eminently aware that low cost-of-ownership packages strike a chord with new car buyers. Extended warranties, free servicing and road side assistance and low rate finance packages are now a staple of many new cars’ offering. If ever proof was needed that the motor trade is in disarray it is surely found in the various incentives offered by distributors at a time when new cars should already be at their most attractive.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The final Car Sales Guide for 2012 has been painstakingly scrutinized as values tend not to fluctuate that much during the first few months of the year. Getting values in appropriate shape in December so as to ensure a smooth transition into January is therefore of the utmost significance. We are pleased to report that some petrol models continue to arrest the gap that had been growing between them and their diesel equivalents. Successful new models from growing brands will also start returning to the market as used vehicles in the New Year and it will be interesting to see how these cars fare against more established competitors.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Motor Trade Publishers would like to take this opportunity to wish all of our subscribers especially those of you, who so very kindly offer us your expertise throughout the year, a happy and peaceful Christmas and best wishes for positive trading conditions in the New Year.</p><p><a href="http://thecarguide.wordpress.com/www.mtp.ie"></a>Aidan Timmons</p></strong></div><p><strong></strong></p><h4></h4>', NULL, 64, 1, 1, '', 1),
